properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong low pressure system which has been giving blizzard conditions to parts of southern Alberta and southwestern Saskatchewan is also affecting the Regina, Weyburn, Estevan, and Carlyle regions, but to a lesser degree. At 3:30 p.m. radar and highway cameras indicated poor visibilities due to snow and blowing snow along and to the south of the Trans-Canada highway - with the worst conditions west of Estevan through to the Alberta border where warnings are in effect. As the system continues tracking towards the Dakotas, the snow and strong winds will improve from northwest to southeast. Regina and Estevan should see improvement this evening and Carlyle overnight. Snowfall amounts over southeastern Saskatchewan will range from 1 to 5 cm, however considerably higher amounts are possible west of Estevan and south of the international border. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2019-04-29T05:38:22-00:00

properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Continues For The Red River From Emerson To The Red River Floodway Channel Inlet
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre continues to issue a Flood Warning on the Red River from Emerson to the Red River Floodway channel inlet due to high water flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-04-29T10:15:00-05:00

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system is tracking northward over northwestern Quebec late this morning. It will bring widespread snow and blowing snow to much of Qikiqtaaluk and eastern portions of Kivalliq. This system is forecast to bring snow and strong northerly winds gusting up to 80 km/h with blizzard conditions to Coral Harbour beginning around noon today and to Naujaat beginning late this afternoon. Conditions will then gradually improve overnight or Monday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A low pressure system moving through southern Saskatchewan brought snow and strong northerly winds to many areas along and south of the Trans-Canada highway today. Strong northerly winds gusting to 70 km/h in combination with falling snow caused visibilities to be significantly reduced in blowing snow. Conditions will begin to improve early this evening near Moose Jaw and late this evening towards the international border. Total snowfall amounts will range from 5 to 10 cm near the Trans-Canada highway to 15 or more cm near the international border. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2019-04-29T10:59:54-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong low pressure system which has been giving heavy snow and blizzard conditions to parts of southern Alberta and Saskatchewan will also affect southern Manitoba but to a much lesser degree. The worst conditions will remain south of the international border as the low tracks into the Dakotas. A mixture of light rain and snow will spread over much of southern Manitoba tonight, however snowfall will be relatively light in most areas. An exception to this will be over the Melita and Killarney regions where there will likely be enough snow tonight to turn the ground white, especially over the higher terrain of the Turtle Mountains where significant accumulations of 10 or more cm are possible. The precipitation will taper off Monday morning as the system weakens and moves off to the east. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2019-04-29T11:47:33-00:00

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A low pressure system which tracked through southern Saskatchewan brought heavy snow and blowing snow to southwestern regions today. Strong northerly winds gusted at times to 80 km/h combined with the falling snow gave blizzard conditions in many areas near and south of the Trans-Canada highway and to the west of the Wascana Basin. Blizzard conditions are expected to improve early this evening around Swift Current and Maple Creek, and later this evening towards Val Marie and Mankota as the snow and wind both diminish. Snowfall totals with this system will range from 10 to 20 cm in many areas, with local amounts over 30 cm in the Cypress Hills. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
